90–Deceased","1355–1408":"1355–1408","1385–Male":"1385–Deceased","1406–Male":"1406–Deceased","1325–1390":"1325–1390","1328–Female":"1328–Deceased","about 1408":"about 1408","1447":"1447","1325":"1325","1355":"1355","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","ABT    1406":"about 1406","about 1385":"about 1385","1408":"1408","1390":"1390","1406":"1406","1328":"1328","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","of Bodorgan,Llangadwaladr,Anglesey,Wales":"Bodorgan, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fychan","type":"LAST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Long, Minh, Muoi, Phan, Phat, Vinh, Cuong, Hien, Hoa, Lam, Lan.  Chinese Wing, Chi, Kin, Cheuk, Chi Wai, Chuen, Hon, Keung, Wah, Wai, Chiu, Ho.","Chinese: alternative Mandarin form of the surname 敖, see   Ao  .","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Auerbach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Moshe, Emanuel, Isidor, Bronia, Chaim, Faigy, Menachem, Meyer, Yechezkel.","German: habitational name from any of several places in southern Germany and Austria called Auerbach ‘the stream at the water meadow’. See also 2,   Au  , and   Bach  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from the town of Auerbach in the Upper Palatinate, Bavaria. Compare   Averbach  ."]},{"name":"Ao","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 敖, meaning both ‘rambling’ and ‘deposed king without posthumous titles’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the personal name of <i>Tai Ao</i> (太敖), teacher of the legendary king Zhuanxu (traditional dates: 2514–2437  BC ). (ii) it is said that the surname is also borne by descendants of deposed kings of the former state of Chu, with no posthumous titles, during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC )."]},{"name":"Auer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Hans, Erwin, Matthias, Siegfried, Bernd, Bernhard, Erna, Franz, Fritz, Hermann, Horst.","German (mainly Bavaria): topographic name for someone living by a water meadow, German <i>Au</i>, or a habitational name for someone from a place called Au or Aue (see   Au   and   Aue  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Czechia, and Slovenia."]}]},{"name":"Leuan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Leuan Fychan ap Ieuan was born in 1350, in Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Ieuan Ap Gruffudd, was 25 and his mother, Annesta Verch Llewelyn, was 22. He had at least 2 sons with Anne verch Gruffydd Fychan. He died in 1447, in his hometown, at the age of 97."},"et":{"1350–1447":"1350–1447","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1355–1408":"1355–1408","1385–Male":"1385–Surnud","1406–Male":"1406–Surnud","1325–1390":"1325–1390","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","about 1408":"umbes 1408","1447":"1447","1325":"1325","1355":"1355","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","ABT    1406":"umbes 1406","about 1385":"umbes 1385","1408":"1408","1390":"1390","1406":"1406","1328":"1328","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","of Bodorgan,Llangadwaladr,Anglesey,Wales":"Bodorgan, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1350–1447":"1350–1447","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","1355–1408":"1355–1408","1385–Male":"1385–Kuollut","1406–Male":"1406–Kuollut","1325–1390":"1325–1390","1328–Female":"132